{{Infobox person | name = Nataliey Bitature | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1990}} | alma_mater = [[Keele University]] and [[Hult International Business School]] | nationality = | citizenship = [[Ugandan]] | Parents = | Known for = }}
'''Nataliey Bitature''' (born 1989) is a [[Ugandan]] social entrepreneur. She is the CEO Energrow, Director of Musana Carts and Chief of Staff Simba Group<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ug.linkedin.com/in/natalieybitature|title=Nataliey Bitature, LinkedIn Profile|last=Bitature|first=Nataliey|date=4 October 2018|website=LinkedIn|archive-url=https://ug.linkedin.com/in/natalieybitature|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>.
==Biography== Bitature was born in 1989 to [[Patrick Bitature]] and Carol Bitature.<ref name=":1" /> She is both a British and [[Ugandan]] citizen.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=http://eagle.co.ug/2016/07/28/bitature-daughter-excels-us1m-competition.html|title=Bitature daughter excels in US1m competition - Eagle Online|last=Reporter|first=Our|date=2016-07-28|work=Eagle Online|access-date=2018-04-24|language=en-US}}</ref>
Bitature earned a Master’s in Social Entrepreneurship from 2015 – 2016 (Sep – Aug) at [[Hult International Business School]]. In 2014, she joined the [[London School of Business and Finance]] ([[LSBF]]) for Emerging Leaders Programme which lasted four months. Bitature also earned her undergraduate degree in Business Management and Education Studies at [[Keele University]] from 2010- 2013.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.worldbank.org/team/nataliey-bitature|title=Nataliey Bitature|last=Bitature|first=Nataliey|date=2017-07-12|website=World Bank Blogs|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> Bitature worked as a Chief Business Development Officer at Tateru Properties, an intern in Investment Banking at [[Stanbic Bank]] [[Uganda]] Limited, [[Uganda]], and as a Business Development Associate Chapter Ten, [[Uganda]].
Bitature is the director of Project 500K, which is a youth empowerment programme aimed at helping young Ugandans become entrepreneurs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.ug/bitature-foundation-aims-empower-500000-ugandan-youth/|title=Bitature Foundation aims to empower 500,000 Ugandan youth|last=|first=|date=|website=Independent.co.ug|publisher=The Independent|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://apearlnews.com/s2018/2018/04/13/tycoon-bitature-roots-for-hard-work/|title=Tycoon Bitature Roots for Hard Work|work=African Pearl News|access-date=2018-04-24|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://chimpreports.com/tycoon-bitature-launches-youth-development-project-as-bishop-lwanga-visits-ibanda/|title=Tycoon Bitature Launches Youth Development Project as Bishop Lwanga Visits Ibanda {{!}} ChimpReports|access-date=2018-04-24|language=en-US}}</ref> The [[World Economic Forum]] named Bitature as one of the Top 5 African Innovators in 2016.<ref name=":2" /> Bitature was a top contender for a US $1 million prize in the Hultz prize competition.<ref name=":1" /> Nataliey was named among [[Forbes 30 Under 30]] in 2018<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbesafrica.com/30-under-30/2018/06/04/under-30-business/attachment/30-nataliey-bitature/|title=30. Nataliey Bitature|last=|first=|date=|publisher=Forbes|website=https://www.forbesafrica.com/30-under-30/2018/06/04/under-30-business/attachment/30-nataliey-bitature/|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=4 October 2018}}</ref>. She also won a Young Achievers Award in 2018 for the Business category<ref name=":5">{{Cite news|url=https://www.sautitech.com/startups/complete-list-winners-at-the-2018-young-achievers-awards/|title=Complete List of Winners at the 2018 Young Achievers Awards|last=|first=|date=|work=Sautitech|access-date=4 October 2018}}</ref>.
==Musana Carts== Bitature, Keisuke Kubota and Manon Lavaud co-founded Musana Carts ("Musana" means sunlight) in [[San Francisco]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.blackbusiness.org/2017/09/musana-solar-powered-food-carts-helping-poor-black-entrepreneurs-uganda-africa.html#more|title=Solar-Powered Food Carts Helping Poor Black Entrepreneurs to Become Street Vendors|website=blog.blackbusiness.org|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> The company offers solar-powered vending carts that can support a fridge and stove.<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":4" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhillfilms.com/article/musana-carts-to-make-street-vendors-lives-better|title=Musana Carts To Make Street Vendor's Lives Better|website=NHILL FILMS|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> The main market is Ugandan street food traders, who are about 80% women according to Bitature.<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=https://www.devex.com/news/innovations-to-jumpstart-the-agricultural-revolution-90098|title=Innovations to jumpstart the agricultural revolution|date=2017-04-20|work=Devex|access-date=2018-04-24|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201606010972.html|title=Uganda: Solar-Powered Cart to Change Life of a Vendor in Kampala|last=Mwesigwa|first=Alon|date=2016-06-01|work=The Observer (Kampala)|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> The street carts are equipped with a battery backup and light, so they can be used at night, and can also be used to charge cell phones and power electronics that take mobile payments. Musana Carts has a relationship with Kampala Capital City Authority and all carts are pre-registered to legally operate within the city.<ref name=":3" /><ref name=":4">{{Cite web|url=https://www.engineering.com/DesignerEdge/DesignerEdgeArticles/ArticleID/12026/Hult-Students-Engineer-Solar-Carts-for-Ugandan-Street-Vendors.aspx|title=Hult Students Engineer Solar Carts for Ugandan Street Vendors|last=ENGINEERING.com|website=www.engineering.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> The company offers [[Microfinance|microfinancing]] services for those who cannot afford to buy a cart outright, as well as training on food processing and safety.<ref name=":4" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2018/01/10/america/1515541812_195391.html|title=Comer fuera: para muchos significa ir a un puesto de comida callejera|last=Belmont|first=Jessica|date=2018-01-10|work=El País|access-date=2018-04-24|language=es|trans-title=Eating out: for many means going to a street food stand|issn=1134-6582}}</ref> Each carts costs about $400.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://venturesafrica.com/meet-the-world-economic-forums-top-five-female-innovators-in-africa/|title=Meet WEF’s top five African female innovators - Ventures Africa|date=2016-05-13|work=Ventures Africa|access-date=2018-04-24|language=en-US}}</ref>
== Other businesses == Bitature also co-founded two service businesses in [[Kampala]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.howwemadeitinafrica.com/start-snapshot-uganda-street-vendors-step-future/54535/|title=Start-up snapshot: Ugandan street vendors step into the future|date=2016-05-25|work=How We Made It In Africa|access-date=2018-04-24|language=en-US}}</ref> Tateru Properties offers real estate services, and Handymen Uganda helps connect customers with contracting services such as painting, plumbing, carpentry, electrical work, paving, landscaping and metal works.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/artsculture/Reviews/Whatever-it-is--they-will-fix-it/691232-2885810-9xtthf/index.html|title=Whatever it is, they will fix it|work=Daily Monitor|access-date=2018-04-24|language=en-UK}}</ref>
