{{Infobox NRHP | name =Paca Street Firehouse | nrhp_type = | image = PacaStreetFirehouse 08 11.jpg | caption = Paca Street Firehouse, August 2011 | location= 106 [[Baltimore-Washington Parkway|North Paca Street]], [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]], [[Maryland]] | coordinates = {{coord|39|17|27|N|76|36|44|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = United States Baltimore#Maryland#USA | built = {{Start date|1909}} | architect = Laferty, J. E. | architecture = Classical Revival | added = October 28, 1983 | area = less than one acre | governing_body = Local | refnum = 83003631<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> }} '''Paca Street Firehouse''', also known as Truck House No. 2, is a historic [[fire station]] located at [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], [[United States]]. The architect of Paca Street Firehouse is John E. Lafferty. It is a 1909 two-story brick structure with a highly detailed stone [[Renaissance Revival]] façade. The principal space is a large room subdivided at the [[Baltimore-Washington Parkway|Paca Street]] end into offices. It is one of three early 20th century firehouses standing and is the only one to retain its original features, particularly in the interior.<ref name="mht_ihp">{{cite web|url=https://mht.maryland.gov/secure/medusa/PDF/NR_PDFs/NR-767.pdf |title=National Register of Historic Places Registration: Paca Street Firehouse|date=September 1983|accessdate=2016-03-01 |author=Peter Kurtze, Gregory Johnson, Larry Hughes, and Timothy Bishop|publisher=Maryland Historical Trust}}</ref>
Paca Street Firehouse was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1983.<ref name="nris"/>
